body:
When setting the **Host header** manually, it is ignored. Here is the code _(the actual domain being replaced with "domain.com")_: 

```
import http from "k6/http";
import { check, sleep } from "k6";

export let options = {
  stages: [{ duration: "1s", target: 10 }],
  insecureSkipTLSVerify: true
};

let i = 0;

export default function() {
  const url = "...";
  let params = { headers: { Host: "domain.com" } };
  const res = http.get(url, params);
  i += 1;
  if (i >= urls.length) i = 0;
  check(res, {
    "status was 200": r => r.status == 200,
    "status was 4xx": r => r.status >= 400 && r.status < 500,
    "status was 5xx": r => r.status >= 500 && r.status < 600,
    "transaction time OK": r => r.timings.duration < 200
  });
  sleep(1);
}
```

@ppcano suggested to open an issue as he said it's likely a bug related to the usage of the go http library:

> I think the header `Host` may be automatically overwritten by the `http` library.
>The following works:
>
>```  http.get("http://localhost:3000", { headers: { myHeader: "hi!" } });```
>
>This may be the reason:
>https://golang.org/pkg/net/http/
>
>``` // For client requests Host optionally overrides the Host
>        // header to send. If empty, the Request.Write method uses
>        // the value of URL.Host. Host may contain an international
>        // domain name.```
